Day 11
1. Git Basics & Repository Setup
â€¢	How to initialize (git init) and clone (git clone) repositories.
â€¢	Understanding local vs. remote and keyed into origin, main/master branches.
2. Branching Strategy
â€¢	Creating new branches: git branch <name>, git checkout -b <name>.
â€¢	Switching and merging: git checkout, git merge.
â€¢	Best practices: branch-per-task workflow for feature isolation and cleaner CI/CD pipelines.
3. Stage, Commit & Reset
â€¢	File lifecycle: untracked â†’ staged (git add) â†’ committed (git commit).
â€¢	Correcting mistakes:
o	Unstage with git reset HEAD <file>.
o	Amend the last commit using git commit --amend.
4. Viewing Changes & History
â€¢	Inspect differences: git diff, git diff --staged.
â€¢	Visualize commit logs:
css
CopyEdit
git log
git log --oneline --graph --decorate --all
Useful during interviews to explain branch structure and merges.
5. Remote Workflows
â€¢	Connect your repo: git remote add origin <url>.
â€¢	Synchronizing code:
o	Push: git push -u origin <branch>.
o	Pull: git pull (fetch + merge) or git fetch followed by git merge.
6. Resolving Conflicts
â€¢	Occurs when merging diverged histories.
â€¢	Manual resolution in conflicting files â†’ git add â†’ git commit.
â€¢	Tip: Demonstrate conflict resolution calmlyâ€”common in collaborative environments.
7. Tagging & Rollbacks
â€¢	Tagging releases: git tag v1.0, push tags via git push origin --tags.
â€¢	Undo strategies:
o	Selective undo: git checkout -- <file>.
o	Local fixes: git reset --soft/<mixed>/<hard> HEAD~1 (use carefully).
o	Public history: git revert <commit>.
8. Git Interview Q&A Highlights
â€¢	Difference: git pull = fetch + merge; git clone includes full history.
â€¢	Explain various reset modes and when to use them.
â€¢	How to push tags and strategies for safe rollback in team environments.
________________________________________
ğŸ¯ Pro Tips for Interviews
â€¢	Always clarify context before troubleshooting or explaining a command.
â€¢	Use real-world scenarios: branching strategy, merge conflicts among multiple team members.
â€¢	Show your ability to fix mistakes gracefullyâ€”commit history management is key.
 
