ğŸŒ± Day 14â€“ My DevOps Journey
ğŸ§  What I Learned Today
Today, I started learning Terraform, one of the most powerful Infrastructure as Code (IaC) tools. I understood how Terraform helps automate infrastructure deployment and how its declarative syntax makes infra setup repeatable, version-controlled, and scalable.
ğŸ§° Tools & Concepts
âœ… What is Terraform?
â€¢	Terraform is an open-source IaC tool from HashiCorp.
â€¢	Used to provision and manage infrastructure using configuration files.
â€¢	Uses HCL (HashiCorp Configuration Language).
âœ… Why Terraform?
â€¢	Automates infrastructure setup.
â€¢	Multi-cloud support (AWS, Azure, GCP).
â€¢	Version-controlled infrastructure (like Git for infra).
â€¢	Declarative â€” define what you want, not how to do it.
ğŸ“¦ My First Terraform Project Steps
1. Install Terraform
â€¢	Downloaded and installed Terraform CLI from the official site.
2. Write Terraform Configuration
provider "aws" {
  region = "ap-south-1"
}

resource "aws_instance" "my_ec2" {
  ami           = "ami-0e670eb768a5fc3d4"
  instance_type = "t2.micro"
  tags = {
    Name = "MyFirstEC2"
  }
}
3. Terraform Commands I Used
Command	Purpose
terraform init	Initializes working directory
terraform plan	Shows what Terraform will do
terraform apply	Applies the configuration and creates resources
terraform destroy	Destroys all resources created
Teraform State File
â€¢	.tfstate file keeps track of the infrastructureâ€™s current state.
â€¢	Needed to compare with the configuration and apply only required changes.
â€¢	Should be stored securely, especially when working in teams (prefer remote backend like S3 + DynamoDB for collaboration).
ğŸ§ª What Iâ€™ll Practice Next
â€¢	Write my own .tf file to deploy EC2, S3, and security groups.
â€¢	Try terraform destroy and understand resource lifecycle.
â€¢	Learn about variables, outputs, and modules.

ğŸ’¬ My Takeaway
â€œTerraform feels like writing the blueprint for infrastructure â€” itâ€™s clear, consistent, and incredibly powerful!â€




ğŸŒ± Day 15 â€“ My DevOps Journey
ğŸ“Œ Topic: Terraform â€“ Providers, Multi-Region/Multi-Cloud, Variables & Conditions
________________________________________
ğŸ§  What I Learned Today
Today I explored how Terraform supports multiple providers, works across different regions and clouds, and how to use variables and conditions to make infrastructure dynamic and scalable.
________________________________________
ğŸ“¦ Key Concepts I Learned
âœ… Terraform Providers
â€¢	Providers are what connect Terraform to cloud platforms like AWS, Azure, or GCP.
â€¢	You can define multiple providers for different regions or even clouds using alias.
provider "aws" {
  region = "us-east-1"
}

provider "aws" {
  alias  = "west"
  region = "us-west-2"
}
________________________________________
âœ… Multi-Region & Multi-Cloud Setup
â€¢	Using provider = aws.west in resources to target different regions.
â€¢	This is great for high availability, disaster recovery, and redundancy.
resource "aws_instance" "web_east" {
  provider = aws
  # ...
}

resource "aws_instance" "web_west" {
  provider = aws.west
  # ...
}
________________________________________
âœ… Variables for Reusability
â€¢	Variables make code dynamic and DRY (Don't Repeat Yourself).
â€¢	I learned how to define and use variables:

variable "region" {
  default = "us-east-1"
}

provider "aws" {
  region = var.region
}
â€¢	Run with:

terraform apply -var="region=us-west-2"
________________________________________
âœ… Conditional Logic in Resources
â€¢	Used count with conditions to create resources only when needed.
count = var.create_instance ? 1 : 0
â€¢	This makes my Terraform code smart and responsive to input flags.
________________________________________
âœ¨ My Takeaway Today
â€œWriting one set of reusable Terraform code that works across multiple regions or clouds makes me feel like an Infra Ninja!â€
